By resolving the forces which it is supposed are the principal forces that put those winds in motion, viz: calorific action of the Sun, and diurna] rotation of the earth, we are led to the conclusion, that the latter is much the greater of the two in its effects upon the trade winds of the northern hemisphere. But not to such an extent is it greater in its effects upon those of the southern. We have seen that those two opposing cur- rents of wind are so unequally balanced that one recedes before the other, and that the current from the southern hemisphere is larger in volume3 i. e.‚ it moves a greater zone or belt of air. The S. E. trade winds discharge themselves over the equator‚—i. e., across a great circle‚—into the region of equatorial calms; while the N. E. trade winds discharge themselves into the same region over a parallel os latitude, and consequently over a small circle.
